{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"219f92e5-5398-4ace-91b0-489dfd18944d","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — crashes from your user\n- **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crashes\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**Other options:**\n\n- Open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n- Run `log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h` for related system logs\n\nOnce you have the `.ips` file, you can symbolicate the .NET runtime frames using `atos` or the Copilot `apple-crash-symbolication` skill if you'd like help resolving native backtraces to source lines.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"58993afb-1725-4bde-8c18-fb86417647e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting — I can answer directly without needing tools.","outputTokens":331,"requestId":"600C:CC8AF:D42BA1:F76AF3:69EACA65"},"id":"75d7ca6a-e32d-4c57-9ef8-23210d97bf5a","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:06.122Z","parentId":"5b539fc8-d2e5-4460-a0d4-4183e7cf8988"}
